7.7.5

Given random variable \(Y\) as a linear function of random variable \(X\), which means \(Y=aX+b\), where \(a,b\in\mathbb{R}\), prove that \(|\sigma_{X,Y}|=1\).



Proof

\(Cov(X,Y)=Cov(X,aX+b)=aV(X)\), \(\sigma_Y=|a|\sigma_X\)

If \(|\sigma_{X,Y}|=1\) for two random variables \(X\) and \(Y\), can we say that \(Y\) must be a linear function of \(X\)?

Proof

yes